crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature fires on the presence of Base64 encoded URI prefixes (http:// and https://) across any file. The simple presence of such strings is not inherently an indicator of malicious content, but is worth further investigation.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a ransomware variant specifically targeting VMware ESXi environments. It recursively traverses directories to find and encrypt files, with a focus on VMware-related extensions such as `.vmdk`, `.vmem`, `.vmx`, and `.vmsn`. The malware drops ransom notes as `.html` and `.txt` files. A key malicious behavior, triggered by the `--esxi` command-line argument, involves executing a shell command via `execl` that uses `vim-cmd` to power off all virtual machines and delete their snapshots. This is a destructive action designed to ensure files are unlocked for encryption and to prevent easy recovery. The malware also overwrites `/etc/motd` to leave a ransom message.
